\par }{\f1\fs20\insrsid5903344 
\par The following query may be used as the context for searching the Projects (we reduce the retrieved data to only the id, but developer may modify it to retrieve all relevant fields):
\par \tab }{\f2\fs20\insrsid5903344 SELECT 
\par \tab \tab project_id
\par \tab FROM
\par \tab \tab project
\par \tab INNER JOIN
\par \tab \tab project_manager
\par \tab \tab ON
\par \tab \tab project_manager.project_id = project.project_id
\par \tab INNER JOIN
\par \tab \tab project_worker
\par \tab \tab ON
\par \tab \tab project_worker.project_id = project.project_id
\par \tab INNER JOIN
\par \tab \tab project_expense
\par \tab \tab ON
\par \tab \tab project_expense.project_id = project.project_id
\par \tab INNER JOIN
\par \tab \tab project_time
\par \tab \tab ON
\par \tab \tab project_time.project_id = project.project_id
\par \tab INNER JOIN
\par \tab \tab project_fix_bill
\par \tab \tab ON
\par \tab \tab project_fix_bill.project_id = project.project_id
\par }{\f1\fs20\insrsid5903344 \tab }{\f2\fs20\insrsid5903344 WHERE
\par }{\f1\fs20\insrsid5903344 
\par From this context, the Search Builder can then add the different WHERE clauses, depending on the filter that was provided.  For example, if a filter for the description was created using createContainsProj
ectManagerFilter, then the Search Builder would add:
\par \tab }{\f2\fs20\insrsid5903344 WHERE (continued from above)
\par \tab \tab project_manager.user_account_id = [value of filter]
\par }{\f1\fs20\insrsid5903344 
